plotdata <- starwars %>%
  count(gender) %>%
  mutate(prop = round(n*100/sum(n), 1),
         lab.ypos = cumsum(prop) - 0.5*prop)
plotdata$label <- paste0(plotdata$gender, "\n",                         round(plotdata$prop), "%")
ggplot(plotdata, 
       aes(x = "", 
           y = prop, 
           fill = gender)) +
  geom_bar(width = 1, 
           stat = "identity", 
           color = "black") +
  geom_text(aes(y = lab.ypos, label = label), 
            color = "black") +
  coord_polar("y", 
              start = 0, 
              direction = -1) +
  theme_void() +
  theme(legend.position = "FALSE") +
  labs(title = "Star Wars Characters by Gender")


# Chapter 3.1.3 Treemap
library(ggplot2)
library(treemapify)
data(starwars)
plotdata <- starwars %>%
  group_by(species) %>%
  summarise(n = n())
ggplot(plotdata, 
       aes(fill = species, 
           area = n, 
           label = species)) +
  geom_treemap() + 
  geom_treemap_text(colour = "white", 
                    place = "centre") +
  labs(title = "Star Wars Characters by Species") +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

# Chapter 4.1.1
library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
plotdata <- starwars %>%
  group_by(gender, species) %>%
  summarize(count = n()) %>%
  mutate(pct = count / sum(count))
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'gender'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
ggplot(plotdata, 
       aes(x = factor(gender), 
           y = pct, 
           fill = species)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity",
           position = "fill",
           show.legend = FALSE) +
  labs(y = NULL, 
       fill = "Species",
       x = NULL,
       title = "Species Distribution by Gender in Star Wars") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set2") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom",
        axis.line = element_blank(),
        axis.text = element_text(size = 12),
        axis.title = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold"),
        plot.title = element_text(size = 16, face = "bold"))

# Chapter 4.3.6
pd <- position_dodge(0.2)
ggplot(starwars, 
       aes(x = factor(eye_color), 
           y = height, 
           group=gender, 
           color=gender)) +
  geom_point(position=pd, 
             size = 3) +
  geom_line(position = pd, 
            size = 1) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = height - height/10, 
                    ymax = height + height/10), 
                width = .1, 
                position = pd, 
                size = 1) +
  scale_y_continuous() +
  scale_color_brewer(palette="Set1") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Height of Star Wars characters by species and gender",
       subtitle = "(mean +/- 10%)",
       x = "", 
       y = "Height (cm)",
       color = "Gender")

ggplot(starwars,
  aes(x = height,
  y = mass,
  color = gender)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .4,
  size = 3) +
  geom_smooth(se=FALSE,
  method = "lm",
  formula = y~poly(x,2),
  size = 1.5) +
  labs(x = "Height (cm)",
  title = "Mass of Star Wars Characters by Gender and Height",
  subtitle = "Data from Star Wars API",
  y = "",
  color = "Gender") +
  scale_y_continuous(label = scales::comma) +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Set1") +
  theme_minimal()


# Chapter 5.2
#create new variable
plotdata <- starwars %>%
  mutate(homeworld_label = case_when(
    homeworld == "Tatooine" ~ "Tatooine",
    homeworld == "Alderaan" ~ "Alderaan",
    homeworld == "Coruscant" ~ "Coruscant",
    homeworld == "Naboo" ~ "Naboo",
    homeworld == "Kamino" ~ "Kamino",
    homeworld == "Stewjon" ~ "Stewjon",
    TRUE ~ "Other"
  )) %>%
  group_by(homeworld_label, species) %>%
  summarize(n = n(),
            mean_height = mean(height),
            sd_height = sd(height),
            se_height = sd_height / sqrt(n))
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'homeworld_label'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
ggplot(plotdata, 
       aes(x = species, 
           y = mean_height,
           color = homeworld_label)) +
  geom_point(size = 3) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = mean_height - se_height, 
                    ymax = mean_height + se_height),
                width = .1) +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 250, 50)) +
  facet_grid(. ~ homeworld_label) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = "none",
        panel.grid.major.x = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor.y = element_blank()) +
  labs(x="", 
       y="Mean Height (cm)", 
       title="Mean Height by Species and Homeworld",
       subtitle = "(Means and standard errors)") +
  scale_color_brewer(palette="Set1")

# Chapter 7.1
library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
data(starwars)
char_height <- starwars %>%
  select(name, height) %>%
  filter(!is.na(height)) %>%
  rename(Close = height) %>%
  mutate(Company = "Star Wars",
         Date = 1:n()) 
ggplot(char_height, 
       aes(x=Date, y=Close, color=Company)) + 
  geom_line(size=1) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, max(char_height$Date), 10),
                     labels = seq(0, max(char_height$Date), 10)) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 250), 
                     breaks = seq(0, 250, 50),
                     labels = seq(0, 250, 50)) +
  labs(title = "Heights of Star Wars Characters",
       y = "Height (cm)") +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Set1")
